'''Eliud Kipchoge''' (born 5 November 1984) is a [[Kenya]]n [[long-distance runner]] who competes the [[marathon]] and formerly [[5000 metres]] race. He won the [[Marathons at the Olympics|Olympic marathon]] in 2016 and is the current [[marathon world record]] holder with a time of 2 hours 1 minute 39 seconds. Kipchoge's world record run at the [[2018 Berlin Marathon]], broke the previous record by 1 minute, 18 seconds, the greatest improvement since 1967. 

Kipchoge won his first individual world championship title in 2003 by winning the junior race at the [[IAAF World Cross Country Championships]] and setting a [[List of junior world records in athletics|world junior record]] over 5000&nbsp;m on the track. At the age of eighteen, he became the senior 5000&nbsp;m world champion at the [[2003 World Championships in Athletics]] with a [[List of World Championships in Athletics records|championships record]], then followed with an Olympic bronze for Kenya in [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004]] and a bronze at the [[2006 IAAF World Indoor Championships]]. A five-time [[5000 metres at the World Championships in Athletics|World Championship 5000&nbsp;m]] finalist, Kipchoge took silver medals at the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|2007 World Championships]], [[2008 Summer Olympics]] and [[2010 Commonwealth Games]].

He switched to [[road running]] in 2012 and made the second-fastest ever [[half marathon]] debut with 59:25 minutes. On his marathon debut he won the 2013 [[Hamburg Marathon]] in a course record time. His first victory at a [[World Marathon Major]] came at the [[Chicago Marathon]] in 2014. He was a three-time winner at both the [[London Marathon]] and [[Berlin Marathon]] between 2015 and 2018. Described as "the greatest marathoner of the modern era",<ref name="veconomist" /> Kipchoge has won 11 of the 12 marathons he has entered, his only loss being to [[Wilson Kipsang Kiprotich]] at the [[2013 Berlin Marathon]] (Kipchoge placed second), where Kipsang broke the world record.<ref name="BBC Sport">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/athletics/24322574|title=Berlin marathon: Wilson Kipsang sets new world record|date=2013-09-29|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>

==Early life and Personal life==
Kipchoge was born on 5 November 1984 in Kapsisiywa, [[Nandi District]] of [[Kenya]]. Kipchoge graduated from Kaptel Secondary School in 1999 but did not run seriously then.<ref name=iaaf/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsportscommunication.nl/athletes/most-successful-athletes/EN11092-Eliud-Kipchoge.aspx|title=Eliud Kipchoge {{!}} Global Sports Communication|website=www.globalsportscommunication.nl|language=en|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> He did run two miles to school on a daily basis.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.runnersworld.com/news/a20793538/the-simple-life-of-one-of-the-worlds-best-marathoners/ | publisher = ''Runners World'' | first = Cathal | last = Dennehy | title = The Simple Life of One of the World’s Best Marathoners | date = 2016-04-19 }}</ref> Kipchoge was raised by a single mother (a teacher), and only knew his father from pictures. He is the youngest of four children. He met his trainer [[Patrick Sang]] (a former Olympic medalist in the steeplechase) in 2001 at the age of 16.<ref name="nytimes201809">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/14/sports/eliud-kipchoge-marathon.html|title=Eliud Kipchoge Is the Greatest Marathoner, Ever|last=Cacciola|first=Scott|date=2018-09-14|publisher=''New York Times''}}</ref>

Kipchoge lives with his wife and 3 children in [[Eldoret]], Kenya.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/article181548434/Berlin-Marathon-2018-Kenianer-Eliud-Kipchoge-knackt-den-Weltrekord.html|title=Berlin-Marathon 2018: Kenianer Eliud Kipchoge knackt den Weltrekord|last=WELT|date=2018-09-16|work=DIE WELT|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/16/sports/eliud-kipchoge-marathon-record.html|title=Berlin Marathon Results: Eliud Kipchoge Breaks World Record|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en}}</ref>

==Career==
===2002–2004===
In 2002, he won at the Kenyan trials for the [[2002 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]] junior race. At the World Cross Country Championships, held in [[Dublin]], Kipchoge finished fifth in the individual race and was part of the Kenyan junior team that won gold. Kipchoge also won the 5000 metres race at the Kenyan trial for the [[2002 World Junior Championships in Athletics]], but got ill and missed the championships. At the [[2003 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]] he won the junior race.

He set a [[List of world junior records in athletics|world junior record]] in the 5000&nbsp;m at the 2003 [[Bislett Games]], running a time of 12:52.61 minutes. This stood as the world and [[List of African junior records in athletics|African junior record]] until 2012, when it was improved to 12:47.53 minutes by [[Hagos Gebrhiwet]] of Ethiopia.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/all-time-toplists/middlelong/5000-metres/outdoor/men/u20?regionType=world&page=1&bestResultsOnly=true&firstDay=1900-01-01&lastDay=2018-09-22 u20 outdoor 5000 Metres men]. IAAF. Retrieved 2018-09-22.</ref>

In July he participated in the Golden League 2004 Roma Meeting. In the 5000 m event, he dipped first among the starters with 12:46.53, which made him the sixth-fastest ever in the event.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/all-time-toplists/middlelong/5000-metres/outdoor/men/senior?regionType=world&page=1&bestResultsOnly=true&firstDay=1900-01-01&lastDay=2018-09-16 5000 Metres All Time] (4 October 2010). Retrieved on 15 October 2010.</ref>

Kipchoge won a gold medal at the [[2003 World Championships in Athletics – Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]] final at the [[2003 World Championships in Athletics|2003 World Championships]], outsprinting both future world record holder [[Kenenisa Bekele]] and runner-up [[Hicham El Guerrouj]] (the world record holder in the [[1500 metres]] and [[mile run|mile]]) by four hundredths of a second (12:52.79 vs. 12:52.83).<ref>2003 World Championships, {{cite news|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/unheralded-kipchoge-salvages-kenyan-pride|title=Unheralded Kipchoge salvages Kenyan pride|publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations|IAAF]]|date=1 September 2003|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>

