During the 2008 Olympics held in Beijing, China, Kipchoge won a silver medal in the 5000m event with a time of 13:02.80; although better than the previous Olympic record of 13:05.59, it was not enough to match Kenenisa Bekele's pace, who won the gold medal for this race.<ref>2008 Olympics, {{cite web|url=http://2008olympics.runnersworld.com/2008/08/mens-5000m-fina.html |title=5000m results |publisher=[[Runner's World]] |accessdate=24 August 2008 |archivedate=25 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080825022924/http://2008olympics.runnersworld.com/2008/08/mens-5000m-fina.html |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> He failed to reach the podium at the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics]], finishing in fifth place and he also finished ninth in the 3000&nbsp;m at the [[2009 IAAF World Athletics Final]]. On the circuit, he won the [[Great Yorkshire Run]] 10K and [[Campaccio]] Cross Country that year.
As the prerace favorite, during the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], Kipchoge gained a gold medal in the [[athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics|marathon]] event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/news/a20818616/mens-marathon-eliud-kipchoge-wins-galen-rupp-gets-bronze/|title=Men’s Marathon: Eliud Kipchoge Wins, Galen Rupp Gets Bronze|date=2016-08-21|work=Runner's World|access-date=2018-10-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/olympics/36727865|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Kenya's Eliud Kipchoge wins men’s marathon|date=2016-08-21|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-kipchoge-of-kenya-wins-men-s-marathon-1471791537-htmlstory.html|title=Rio Olympics: Eliud Kipchoge of Kenya wins men's marathon; Galen Rupp of the U.S. takes bronze|last=Dillman|first=Lisa|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref> On the last day of the Rio Olympics on 21 August 2016 he won in a time of 2:08:44. The runner up was Feyisa Lilesa (Ethiopia) 2:09:54 and the bronze medal went to Galen Rupp (USA), doing his second marathon, crossing the finish line in 2:10:05. When the halfway point after 21.0975&nbsp;km was reached, 37 men where within 10 seconds of the lead runner. The participants field diminished to 3 lead runners shortly before 34&nbsp;km. Kipchoge made his final move on silver medal winner Lilesa around 36&nbsp;km into the race. He covered the first half of the race in 65:55, while doing the second half in 62:49, that amounts to a difference of more than 3 minutes, a negative split.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/rio-2016-men-marathon|title=IAAF: Report: men's marathon – Rio 2016 Olympic Games{{!}} News {{!}} iaaf.org|website=iaaf.org|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref><ref name="Ingle">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/21/eliud-kipchoge-callum-hawkins-feyisa-lilesa-olympic-marathon|title=Eliud Kipchoge powers to marathon gold as Callum Hawkins finishes ninth|last=Ingle|first=Sean|date=2016-08-21|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref> The winning gap between Kipchoge and Lilesa by 70 seconds is the largest victory margin since the 1972 Olympic marathon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flotrack.org/articles/5054839-eliud-kipchoge-wins-olympic-marathon-galen-rupp-takes-bronze|title=Eliud Kipchoge Wins Olympic Marathon, Galen Rupp Takes Bronze|access-date=2018-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Kipchoge's wining time of 2:08:44 is his slowest marathon time (as of Sep 2018). One hundred fifty-five runners started the race, which amounted to the largest field in Olympic history; 139 of them finished the race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/olympic-games/the-xxxi-olympic-games-5771/results/men/marathon/final/result|title=IAAF: Marathon Result {{!}} The XXXI Olympic Games {{!}} iaaf.org|website=iaaf.org|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/sports/article/17359189/eliud-kipchoge-kenya-wins-olympic-men-marathon-american-galen-rupp-takes-bronze|title=Eliud Kipchoge of Kenya wins Olympic men's marathon; American Galen Rupp takes bronze|work=espnW|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref> With this win, Kipchoge became the second Kenyan male after Sammy Wanjiru in Beijing 2008 to win an Olympic marathon gold medal. At the same Olympics, the women marathon was one by another Kenyan, Jemima Sumgong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/14/jemima-sumgong-wins-olympic-marathon-gold-kenya|title=Jemima Sumgong wins Olympic marathon gold for Kenya|last=Reuters|date=2016-08-14|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref><ref name="Ingle"/>

===2010–11 seasons===
He made his debut on the [[2010 IAAF Diamond League]] by winning the 5000&nbsp;m [[Qatar Athletic Super Grand Prix]] in a meet record time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ramsak|first=Bob|date=14 May 2010|publisher=IAAF |accessdate=27 April 2016|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/rudisha-and-powell-impress-as-iaaf-diamond-le|title=Rudisha and Powell impress as IAAF Diamond League kicks off in Doha – Report}}</ref>

Kipchoge then went on to enter the Carlsbad 5000 in CA, USA. The Carlsbad 5&nbsp;km road race is the venue for the world best times for a 5k road race for men and women respectively. The fastest to cover the track was Sammy Kipketer in 2000, with 12:59.5 min.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arrs.run/working_groups_road_records_english.php|title=ARRS - Association of Road Racing Statisticians|website=arrs.run|language=en|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> Kipchoge made a world best attempt and although he won the race, weather affected his chances and he finished in 13:11, the fourth-fastest ever for the course up to that point in time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cruz|first =Dan|date=12 April 2010|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/defar-and-kipchoge-prevail-in-carlsbad|title=Defar and Kipchoge prevail in Carlsbad|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>

In the first athletics final of the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]], he attempted to win the 5000&nbsp;m Commonwealth title. Ugandan runner [[Moses Kipsiro]] held a slender lead over him in the final stages of the race and Kipchoge ended up in second place, taking the silver medal some seven hundredths of a second behind.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/commonwealth_games/delhi_2010/9067230.stm Commonwealth Games 2010: Kipsiro wins 5,000m gold]. [[BBC Sport]] (6 October 2010). Retrieved 6 October 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rowbottom |first=Mike |date=12 October 2010 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=58496.html |title=India sweeps women’s Discus Throw, Langat and Kipsiro complete doubles – Commonwealth Games Day Six |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=15 October 2010 |archivedate=15 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015004142/http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind%3D100/newsid%3D58496.html |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> He flew back to Europe immediately after to take part in the [[Belgrade Race through History]] the following day. His shoe fell off in the first kilometre and, after putting it back on, he made up much ground on the field to eventually take second place two seconds behind [[Josphat Menjo]].<ref>{{cite news|last= Butcher|first=Pat|date=13 October 2010|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/menjo-takes-five-seconds-off-course-record-in|title=Menjo takes five seconds off course record in Belgrade|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>

At the start of 2011, he won the short race at the [[Great Edinburgh Cross Country]], ahead of [[Asbel Kiprop]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wenig|first=Jörg|date=8 January 2011|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=27 April 2016|url= http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/kipchoge-and-masai-prevail-in-snowy-edinburgh|title=Kipchoge and Masai prevail in snowy Edinburgh}}</ref> He attempted to retain his title at the Carlsbad 5000 in April but came a close second behind [[Dejen Gebremeskel]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Cruz|first=Dan|date=4 April 2011|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/gebremeskel-and-kiros-take-carlsbad-5km-victo|title=Gebremeskel and Kiros take Carlsbad 5Km victories|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> In May he raced the [[3000 metres]] (finished third) in Doha, with a time of 7:27.66 and ranked him as the 12th-fastest at the distance up to this point.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alltime-athletics.com/m_3000ok.htm|title=Men's 3000m|website=www.alltime-athletics.com|access-date=2018-09-18}}</ref> Kipchoge was chosen to represent Kenya at the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics]] and reached the 5000&nbsp;m final for the fifth consecutive time, although he only managed seventh place on this occasion.

===2012 onwards - Move to road events===
'''2012'''

Kipchoge returned to the Edinburgh Cross Country in 2012, but this time he finished third behind Asbel Kiprop and Britain's [[Jonathan Hay (athlete)|Jonathan Hay]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wenig|first=Jorg|date=7 January 2012|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/kiprop-triumphs-in-race-of-champions-bekele-a|title=Kiprop triumphs in race of champions, Bekele a distant 11th – Edinburgh XC report|publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations|IAAF]]|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> He was also third at the [[Carlsbad 5000]] in March.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rosenthal|first=Bert|date=2 April 2012|accessdate=27 April 2016 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/gebremeskel-dibaba-win-carlsbad-5000|title=Gebremeskel and Dibaba Win Carlsbad 5000|publisher=IAAF}}</ref> He attempted to gain a place on the 10,000&nbsp;m Olympic team at the [[Prefontaine Classic]], but fell back in the late stages of the Kenyan trial race, finishing seventh.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gains|first=Paul|date=2 June 2012|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=27 April 2016|url= http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/dibaba-302439-and-kiprop-270198-on-stunning-b|title=Dibaba 30:24.39 and Kiprop 27:01.98 on stunning but wet first night in Eugene&nbsp;– Samsung Diamond League}}</ref> A seventh-place finish in the Kenyan 5000&nbsp;m trial race meant he would not make a third consecutive Olympic team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mutuota|first=Mutwiri|date=23 June 2012|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=27 April 2016|url= http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/rudisha-runs-14212-at-altitude-kenyan-olymp|title=Rudisha runs 1:42.12 at altitude&nbsp;– Kenyan Olympic Trials}}</ref>

He made his [[half marathon]] debut in the [[Lille Half Marathon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/chebii-clocks-5905-course-record-in-lille-hal|title=Chebii clocks 59:05 course record in Lille Half Marathon|last=Ramsak|first=Bob|date=2 September 2012|accessdate=19 January 2013|publisher=IAAF|last2=Juck|first2=Alfons}}</ref> The run was won by a new course record time of 59:05 (previously 59:36 by ilahun Regassa set in 2008) from Ezekiel Chebii (former pb 59:22), trailed by Bernard Koech 59:10, and Kipchoge earned a third place with 59:25. His time of 59:25 became the second fastest Half Marathon debut, only second to Moses Mosop's 59:20 in Milan in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/news/chebii-clocks-5905-course-record-in-lille-hal|title=IAAF: Chebii clocks 59:05 course record in Lille Half Marathon{{!}} News {{!}} iaaf.org|website=iaaf.org|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref>

Kipchoge entered the [[2012 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships]] and placed sixth.<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships Results|url=https://www.iaaf.org/results/iaaf-world-half-marathon-championships/2012/iaaf-world-half-marathon-championships-4862/men/half-marathon/final/result|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref>

'''2013'''

[[File:Wilson Kipsang Kiprotich running world record at Berlin marathon 2013.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|left|
Wilson Kipsang (front) and Kipchoge (behind) running in the Berlin Marathon 2013 in which Kipsang set the world record with 2:03:23 and Kipchoge, racing in his second marathon, finished second, 42 seconds later. As of October 2018, Berlin 2013 is Kipchoge's only loss in the 12 marathons he has raced.
]]

Kipchoge opened his 2013 season with a win at the [[Barcelona Half Marathon]] in a time of one hour and four seconds.<ref>[http://mitjabarcelona.com/resultados/2013/ Results]. MitjaBarcelona. Retrieved 22 April 2013.</ref> Making his [[marathon]] debut in April, he demonstrated a smooth transition to the longer distance by taking the [[Hamburg Marathon]] title with a run of 2:05:30 hours—beating the field by over two minutes and setting a new course record.<ref>{{cite news|last=Minshull|first=Phil|date=21 April 2013|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/kipchoge-makes-marvellous-marathon-debut-with|title=Kipchoge makes marvellous Marathon debut with 2:05:30 course record in Hamburg|publisher=IAAF|accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref> In August 2013, he won the Half Marathon of [[Klagenfurt]] in 61:02 minutes.<ref>[http://results.kleinezeitung.at/results/show_results_db.php?veranstnr=12284&racenr=1 Klagenfurt – Kärnten läuft – Halbmarathon – 2013-08-18] Retrieved 19 August 2013.</ref>

Then, he raced in the Berlin Marathon and he finished second in 2:04:05, the fifth-fastest time in history, behind [[Wilson Kipsang Kiprotich|Wilson Kipsang]], who set a new marathon world record with 2:03:23. The third place went to Geoffrey Kipsang (Kenia) with 2:06:26.<ref name="BBC Sport"/> This made him the fifth-fastest marathon runner in history, in his second ever marathon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/wilson-kipsang-sets-world-record-of-20323-in|title=IAAF: Kipsang sets world record of 2:03:23 at Berlin Marathon{{!}} News {{!}} iaaf.org|website=iaaf.org|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>

'''2015'''

Kipchoge won the Berlin Marathon in 2015. His win and then-personal-best time (2:04:00) occurred even though his shoes malfunctioned, causing his insoles to flap out of both shoes from 10&nbsp;km onward; rather than risk time lost from an adjustment, he finished the race with bloodied, blistered feet.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/news/a20853873/kipchoge-wins-berlin-marathon-despite-shoe-malfunction/|first=Cathal|last=Dennehy|title=
Despite Insoles Coming Loose, Eliud Kipchoge Wins Berlin Marathon|date=2015-09-27|access-date=2018-09-30|publisher=''Runner's World''}}</ref>

'''2016'''

In April 2016, Kipchoge won the London Marathon for the second consecutive year in a time of 2:03:05.<ref>[http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2635264-london-marathon-2016-results-men-and-womens-top-finishers.] Retrieved 22 May 2016.</ref> His performance broke the course record in London, and became the second-fastest marathon time in history, missing [[Dennis Kimetto]]'s world record by 8 seconds.<ref>[https://www.iaaf.org/records/all-time-toplists/road-running/marathon/outdoor/men/senior?regionType=world&drop=regular&fiftyPercentRule=regular&page=1&bestResultsOnly=true&firstDay=1899-12-31&lastDay=2016-04-24] Retrieved 20 September 2018.</ref>

On 20 November 2016, Kipchoge ran in the Airtel [[Delhi Half Marathon]], winning the race clocking a time of 59:44.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.omriyadat.com/african-athletics/kenya-eliud-kipchoge-marathon|title=Rio 2016: Kenya's Kipchoge triumphs in men's marathon|publisher=OmRiyadat English|accessdate=21 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018073703/http://en.omriyadat.com/african-athletics/kenya-eliud-kipchoge-marathon|archivedate=18 October 2016|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

'''2017'''

On 6 May 2017, Kipchoge, along with [[Zersenay Tadese]] (world record holder in the half marathon) and [[Lelisa Desisa]] (2 time Boston Marathon winner) attempted the first sub-two-hour assisted marathon, in the Nike [[Breaking2]] project on the [[Monza]] [[Autodromo Nazionale Monza|Formula 1 racetrack]] near [[Milan, Italy]]. It was paced by a lead car and supporting runners joining in stages (both considered illegal under [[IAAF]] rules).<ref name="veconomist" >{{cite news|author=J.S.|title=Can the marathon’s two-hour barrier be broken?|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/gametheory/2017/10/runnin-down-dream|work=[[The Economist]]|date=4 October 2017}}</ref> The race started at 5:45h local time on the 2.4&nbsp;km track. Kipchoge finished in 2:00:25, while the other two had to slow and finished far behind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.herbertsteffny.de/artikel/Nike_Sub_2Hours.htm|title=Sub 2:00 Hours Marathon - kritisch hinterfragt|website=www.herbertsteffny.de|language=de-de|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> The runners planned even 14:13 5k splits to break 2 hours. His 5k splits were: 14:14, 14:07, 14:13, 14:15, 14:14, 14:17, 14:17, 14:27, and 6:20 to finish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2017/may/06/sub-two-hour-marathon-attempt-in-monza-live|title=Eliud Kipchoge misses sub two-hour marathon target in Monza – as it happened|last=Caroll|first=James|date=2017-05-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The 5k split times from 25k and further would be world records: 25k in 1:11:03, 30k in 1:25:20, 35k in 1:39:37, 40k in 1:54:04.

On 24 September 2017, he won the Berlin Marathon in a time of 2:03:32.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bmw-berlin-marathon.com/en/news-and-media/news/2017/09/24/eliud-kipchoge-wins-dramatic-race-in-berlin-with-world-leading-time.html|title=BMW BERLIN-MARATHON|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>
In rainy conditions, he finished 14 seconds ahead of [[Guye Adola]] who ran his first marathon.
Adola set the fastest marathon debut ever.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bz-berlin.de/berlin/44-berlin-marathon-eliud-kipchoge-ergebnis-zeit-weltrekord|title=44. Berlin-Marathon: Eliud Kipchoge siegt, Weltrekord verpasst|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>
Former marathon world record holder Wilson Kipsang and 2016 winner Kenenisa Bekele failed to finish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/article168971522/Kipchoge-schrammt-am-Weltrekord-vorbei.html|title=Berlin-Marathon: Eliod Kipchoge schrammt am Weltrekord vorbei|last=SUF|date=2017-09-24|work=DIE WELT|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbb24.de/sport/thema/2017/berlin-marathon-2017/beitraege/44-berlin-marathon-strecke-lauf-sonntag.html|title=Favorit Kipchoge gewinnt den 44. Berlin-Marathon|website=www.rbb24.de|language=de|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>

'''2018'''

{{quote box
| width = 30%|'''''"A 2:01:39 in the Marathon is like a Mars landing for Space travel."|''[[Neue Zürcher Zeitung]]'''''''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzz.ch/sport/weshalb-der-juengste-marathon-weltrekord-erklaerbar-ist-ld.1420538|title= Why the latest marathon world record is explainable (Weshalb der jüngste Marathon-Weltrekord erklärbar ist) |access-date=2018-09-17|newspaper=[[Neue Zürcher Zeitung]]|language=German}}</ref>
}}

{{quote box
| width = 30%|'''''"Whatever happens, this will surely go down as Kipchoge’s crowning glory, his marathon opus. It would be no surprise if his record stood for a generation, unless, of course, he himself has other ideas."|''[[The Guardian]]'''''''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/sep/16/eliud-kipchoge-smashes-world-marathon-record-berlin|title= Eliud Kipchoge smashes world marathon record by 78 seconds in Berlin   |access-date=2018-10-01|newspaper=The Guardian|language=English}}</ref>
}}

{{quote box
| width = 30%|'''''"In an astonishing performance at the 2018 BMW Berlin Marathon, Kipchoge took marathoning into a new stratosphere by clocking 2:01:39 — the first man ever under 2:02, and a full 78 seconds faster than Dennis Kimetto’s four-year-old world record.
'''''
It was a performance so far superior to anything we’ve seen before that comparing it to another marathon feels inadequate. This was Wilt Chamberlain’s 100-point game in basketball, Usain Bolt’s 9.58 in the 100-meter dash.
'''''
Kipchoge’s splits — 61:06 for the first half, a ridiculous 60:33 for his second half — sound made up. But they were real, and they were spectacular."'''''"|''LetsRun.com'''''''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.letsrun.com/news/2018/09/greatest-ever-20139-eliud-kipchoge-crushes-world-record-win-2018-berlin-marathon/|title= The Greatest Ever – 2:01:39 – Eliud Kipchoge Crushes World Record to Win 2018 Berlin Marathon|access-date=2018-10-03||language=English}}</ref>
}}

Kipchoge won the [[2018 London Marathon]] against a field that included [[Mo Farah]] (4 time Olympic gold medalist), who finished third with a time of 2:06:32 in his second marathon, [[Kenenisa Bekele]] (3 time Olympic gold medalist + World Record holder 5000 m and 10000 m), and defending champion [[Daniel Wanjiru]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eurosport.de/leichtathletik/olympiasieger-kipchoge-siegt-beim-london-marathon-farah-mit-britischem-rekord_sto6723468/story.shtml|title=London-Marathon mit Hattrick durch Kipchoge und Rekord für Farah|date=2018-04-22|work=Eurosport Deutschland|access-date=2018-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/athletics/43855468|title=London Marathon 2017: Mo Farah finishes third as Eliud Kipchoge wins|date=2018-04-22|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-04-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzz.ch/sport/kenenisa-bekele-der-koenig-im-sauseschritt-ld.1387169|title=Kenenisa Bekele: Der König im Sauseschritt {{!}} NZZ|last=Geisser|first=Remo|date=2018-05-19|work=Neue Zürcher Zeitung|access-date=2018-09-17|language=de-CH|issn=0376-6829}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2018/apr/22/london-marathon-2018-live|title=London Marathon 2018: Kipchoge wins men's race with Farah third as Cheruiyot takes women's—as it happened|last=Harris|first=Daniel|date=2018-04-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2018-04-30|last2=bit)|first2=Will Unwin (for a|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=London Marathon 2015 men results, Eliud Kipchoge wins|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/london-marathon/11559741/london-marathon-2015-results-winners-men.html|last=Bloom|first=Ben|date=26 April 2015|accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>[[File:Eliud Kipchoge at Berlin Marathon 2018 04.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Eliud Kipchoge (left) and his three pacemakers (right) about 30 minutes into the run, during the Marathon world record in the 2018 Berlin Marathon. He is shown a few seconds before crossing the river Spree.]]

On 16 September 2018, Kipchoge won the Berlin Marathon in a time of 2:01:39, breaking the previous world record by 1 minute and 18 seconds (2:02:57 set by fellow countryman Dennis Kimetto at the Berlin Marathon in 2014). In statements before the race, he said, he planned to run a new personal best.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/14/sports/eliud-kipchoge-marathon.html|title=Eliud Kipchoge Is the Greatest Marathoner, Ever|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref> He finished 4:43 min ahead of second placed fellow Kenyan Amos Kipruto. The World Record holder from 2013, Wilson Kipsang of Kenia, came in third in 2:06:48.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/article181548434/Berlin-Marathon-2018-Kenianer-Eliud-Kipchoge-knackt-den-Weltrekord.html|title=Berlin-Marathon 2018: Kenianer Eliud Kipchoge knackt den Weltrekord|last=WELT|date=2018-09-16|work=DIE WELT|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/wilson-kipsang-sets-world-record-of-20323-in|title=IAAF: Kipsang sets world record of 2:03:23 at Berlin Marathon{{!}} News {{!}} iaaf.org|website=iaaf.org|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref> From 2003 onwards, all previous 6 world records in the men's marathon were set at the Berlin marathon.<ref>
http://www.aipsmedia.com/2018/09/17/23450/marathon-iaaf-berlin-eliud-kipchoge-profile
</ref> Kipchoge began the race with three [[Pacemaker (running)|pacemakers]] dedicated to him. After 5&nbsp;km in the run, the gap between him and the Kipsang group was 9 seconds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/article181548434/Berlin-Marathon-2018-Kenianer-Eliud-Kipchoge-knackt-den-Weltrekord.html|title=Berlin-Marathon 2018: Kenianer Eliud Kipchoge knackt den Weltrekord|last=WELT|date=2018-09-16|work=DIE WELT|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> After 15&nbsp;km in the race, two of the pacemakers were unable to continue pacing him. The remaining pacemaker dropped out after 25 kilometers, leaving Kipchoge to cover the final 17&nbsp;km alone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/berlin-marathon-2018-eliud-kipchoge-world-rec|title=Kipchoge Breaks Marathon World Record in Berlin with Stunning 2:01:39|last=|first=|date=2018-09-16|website=IAAF|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Kipchoge had planned to run with a pacemaker though 30&nbsp;km (rather than 25&nbsp;km); this adversity "was unfortunate," he reflected post-race, "but I had to believe".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.si.com/olympics/2018/09/16/eliud-kipchoge-breaks-marathon-world-record-greatest-marathoner-all-time-berlin-results|first=Chris|last=Chavez|date=2018-09-16|title=Olympics Eliud Kipchoge Breaks Marathon World Record, Cements Himself As The Greatest Of All-Time|work='Sports Illustrated'}}</ref> Kipchoge accelerated, covering the second half (1:00:34) of the race faster than the first half (1:01:06).<ref>{{cite news |last=Ingle |first=Sean |date=2018-09-16 |title=Eliud Kipchoge smashes world marathon record by 78 seconds in Berlin |url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/sep/16/eliud-kipchoge-smashes-world-marathon-record-berlin |work='The Guardian' |access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref>  In sunny weather conditions, the temperature was 14&nbsp;°C (57&nbsp;°F) during the start and 18&nbsp;°C (64&nbsp;°F) when Kipchoge crossed the finish line.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzz.ch/sport/eliud-kipchoge-laeuft-einen-marathon-weltrekord-fuer-die-geschichte-ld.1420500|title=Eliud Kipchoge läuft einen Marathon-Weltrekord für die Geschichte {{!}} NZZ|last=Wirz|first=Jürg|date=2018-09-17|work=Neue Zürcher Zeitung|access-date=2018-09-17|language=de-CH|issn=0376-6829}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/athletics/news/berlin-marathon-2018-eliud-kipchoge-smashes-marathon-world/emhpp8yvfrmw1bw56uhyfc0ef|title=Berlin Marathon 2018: Eliud Kipchoge smashes marathon world record, wins third Berlin Marathon|website=www.sportingnews.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.si.com/olympics/2018/09/16/eliud-kipchoge-breaks-marathon-world-record-greatest-marathoner-all-time-berlin-results|title=Eliud Kipchoge destroys marathon world record in 2:01:39|work=SI.com|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en}}</ref>

The prize money Kipchoge made for his Berlin run altogether was 120.000 €. This comes down to 30.000 € for finishing in less than 2:04 hours, 40.000 for his win and additionally 50.000 € for a new world record.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/article181548434/Berlin-Marathon-2018-Kenianer-Eliud-Kipchoge-knackt-den-Weltrekord.html|title=Berlin-Marathon 2018: Kenianer Eliud Kipchoge knackt den Weltrekord|last=WELT|date=2018-09-16|work=DIE WELT|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> The world record done during this run is the 8th world record in the men's marathon at the Berlin marathon in a 20 years timeframe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/sport/article181548434/Berlin-Marathon-2018-Kenianer-Eliud-Kipchoge-knackt-den-Weltrekord.html|title=Berlin-Marathon 2018: Kenianer Eliud Kipchoge knackt den Weltrekord|last=WELT|date=2018-09-16|work=DIE WELT|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref>

The pace during the run averaged to a 2:53/km or 4:38/mile. The second half of the race in 60:34 is faster than all but three American half-marathon times (the last 10k was covered in 28:33.).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/news/a23279362/eliud-kipchoge-marathon-world-record/|title=Amazing Stats from Eliud Kipchoge’s Marathon World Record|date=2018-09-17|work=Runner's World|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://runningmagazine.ca/sections/runs-races/kipchoges-world-record-setting-berlin-marathon-deconstructed/|title=Kipchoge's world-record-setting Berlin marathon deconstructed - Canadian Running Magazine|date=2018-09-18|work=Canadian Running Magazine|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> It was the most evenly paced marathon ever run, with the fastest 5k Intervall covered in 14:18 and the slowest in 14:37, a difference of 19 seconds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzz.ch/sport/weshalb-der-juengste-marathon-weltrekord-erklaerbar-ist-ld.1420538|title=Weshalb der jüngste Marathon-Weltrekord erklärbar ist {{!}} NZZ|last=Geisser|first=Remo|date=2018-09-17|work=Neue Zürcher Zeitung|access-date=2018-10-10|language=de-CH|issn=0376-6829}}</ref> His split times during his world record were as follows:<ref name="auto"/><ref>https://runningmagazine.ca/sections/runs-races/kipchoges-world-record-setting-berlin-marathon-deconstructed/</ref>

